The paper deals with the complexity of motion planning for a single robot, which is a common problem in robotics (cs.RO). The paper also involves analyzing the computational complexity of the problem, which falls under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC). The use of gadgets and their states to model the problem is a common technique in artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also involves analyzing the connectivity of the gadgets, which is a problem in graph theory and data structures (cs.DS). Finally, the paper mentions the possibility of restricting the gadgets to avoid crossings in the plane, which is a problem in computational geometry (cs.CG).
